Couples who violate this policy may have to pay enormous fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and to suffer discrimination at the workplace.
The Chinese authorities have assigned the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some authorities forced pregnant women from a second child to abort.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high ratio of boys and girls.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually adopted their position on the policy of the single child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for residents of cities, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already single children -- and in 2007, they added many of their hard slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, professor at the Institute of Population Research, at the University of Beijing, stated that the central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In a matter of time, posters encouraging families to have only one child have been replaced by copies of detailed regulations that have the right to have a second child and how to apply for authorisation.
The city's government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples, at their home, and slide prospectuses at their door.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those wishing to have more than one child.
According to the family planning manager, the answer was disappointing.
Dissatisfied response
Although managers in a rural town in the Shanghai suburbs say they have seen an increase in requests for couples' files wishing for a second child after the campaign was launched, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still expected to be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than 2009 but less than 2008.
Feng Juying, Head of the Family Planning Committee in the municipality of Caolu in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people do not want to have children anymore.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27 years old and his wife Liu Juanjuan, 26 years old, stated that they would worship two children and that they were legally authorized to do so.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and the life insurance provided by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
The West consider the policy of the single child to be a right issue, says Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is pregnant for seven months from the first child of the couple.
True, we steal the chance of having more than one child.
But the problem is not just the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she wanted only a single child because she was one of her own. "We were the center of the family and we had the habit of everyone taking care of us."
We don't have the habit of caring for someone else and we really don't want to take care of others."
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company, says it more cruelly.
For couples working in two, middle class, which reduces the birth rate, he says, it is necessary to be selfish as well as successful.
People aged 20 or 30 grew up seeing their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and do not want to have this lifestyle themselves, he said.
