The United Nations Group has plans for emission reduction
The conference on climate, sponsored by the United Nations -- so far, characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- has returned under the light of the Friday ramp, because of the publication of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialised nations with most burdens, in the near future.
The text that could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases highlighted the remaining obstacles, as long as it clarified the path to be taken.
But it has been seen as an important advance in the negotiations that lack time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving next week in Copenhagen.
Drafted by a United Nations ad hoc working group, the text does not say how many rich countries would give to the poor to support climate, in the short term and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of global warming that those responsible would be prepared to tolerate.
He gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequiyt, Representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the Executive Secretary-General described on the climate change of the United Nations, Yvo de Boer, as "the full picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions from 25 to 45 per cent in 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would reduce their emissions from 15 to 30 per cent during the same period.
Together, countries would reduce emissions between 50 and 95 per cent by 2050.
The European Union has also resumed negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to support floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal changes occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, United States representative for climate negotiations, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared with the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if these were not financed by developed countries.
This change is the signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher towards China than the Bush administration was, two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that reductions could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments one hour after the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei stated that the US chief negotiator, either lacks "good sense", or was "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not financially help China to combat climate warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major global powers at stake, defects occur both in the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing about their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist on the fact that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the main powers were fighting to know who should be costed by the reduction in greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to make major emitters responsible for their actions.
It is really a game in which a new economic hegemony is developed, Ulate said, who is also the Climate Adviser for Mexico and Central America for International Conservation.
Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to put pressure on them to obtain a treaty legally binding in Copenhagen, although most major participants said that negotiations would lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which meets 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Arthur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission's climate unit, said that the small island states' action "has put political pressure on the complete political process", in part because they are now united and they ask emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The discussions became an urgent matter, while delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the problems in court before the heads of government reached an agreement.
High-level officials such as the Minister of the Environment of India, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister came down from their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend house-to-house meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be studied during the following week.
The true image of the assembly -- during which 13,000 people enter and leave the Palais des Congresses every day -- guitar players present night performances that mock, betray and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity only increases: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We enter the Grand Court, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice-President of the International Conservation Policy.
