75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Work discrimination has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Fecondity and professional career of women in Spain" carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 does not leave any doubt: 75% of the working mothers have seen their limited professional career due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences between the beginning of life and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment employed.
Those who do not have activity outside the house, work part-time or have little stable work, get married sooner, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women who have stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are able to re-enter marriage and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age have their first child, on average, 3.7 years of age after being installed in a couple. This figure goes to 4.1 for those working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to withdraw the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised has a wide influence on maternity, but less on the date of the beginning of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that increases the gap between the age of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education is, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who conducted elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have conducted elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have had middle-level or higher-level studies reverse this program and give priority to getting a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Ms. Delgado.
