As this has happened with the ABS brakes anti-lock system and as this will happen with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory part of European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered light commercial cars and vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of shortage has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's objective is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its way of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system through the driver's kick.
But the latter doesn't always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident could not rely on the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in return, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
